Next I divided the data into two groups byt quality. High quality group contains the observations receiving 7 or 8, and the low quality group which contains the observations receiving 3 or 4. After looking at the data there may be a correlation with quality based in the volatile acid, density, and citric acid. The graphs below will show the data differences.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 4,899 white wines that where tested with 12 features on the property of the wine. (fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality)

Other observations: The median quality of white wine rating is 6. Most of the wines have a density around .5. The median percent of alcohol is 10.4 and the max is 14.2.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

My main feature of interest is the wine quality and if there is a connection between the quality and some or all of the collected items.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I beleive that alcohol, acidity, and residual.sugar will have a relationship to perceived quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created a variable called quality.level that will divide the quality into categories or low, average, and high. This will make dividing up the data by quality easier.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

The citric acid contained some unusual distributions. The data was already clean so no modifications or cleaning was necessary.

Bivariate Plots Section

The graph shows that the high and average quality wines have lower volatile acidty than the lower rated wines.

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  white_Wine_data$quality and white_Wine_data$alcohol
## t = 33.858, df = 4896, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4126015 0.4579941
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.4355747

With the correlation coefficient of 0.435, the graph shows a positive relationship between alcohol and quality level. Average quality and low quality wines have their percent alcohol contents concentrated around 10 whereas high quality wines have their percent alcohol contents concentrated around 12.

##

The correlation coefficient is -0.7, this shows that as the alcohol content increases the density decreases. # Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

I observed a negative relationship between citric acid and volatile acidity, and a positive coorelation between quality level and alcohol.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Yes, I observed that as alcohol content increases the density decreases.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Quality is positively correlated with the alcohol content.

Multivariate Analysis

Quality has a strong positive relationship with the % of alcohol and the density. It may be possible to make a predictive model that can predict the quality of wide based on % of alcohol and density.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

When looking at wine quality level, there is a positive relationship between density and alcohol.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

I feel like residual sugar should have an effect on the flavor but it had little impact on wine quality.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The distribution of white wine quality is normal. The average quality wines make up 74.6% of the observations. There are no wines ranked 1,2, or 10.

Plot Two

Description Two

Citric Acid seems to have no correlation with quality. It is surprising that the average for all three quality levels appears to be the same. The acidity of a wine can greatly change the flavor but it did not seem to effect the results.

Plot Three

Description Three

It appears that white wines that are rated higher have a higher alcohol content and lower volatile acidity. In conclusion alcohol and volatile acidity are an important factor in the quality of whie wines.

###Reflection

The white wines data set contains ratings on 4898 white wines. To understand the dataset I first graphed the provided data to find questions that I wanted to answer. After figuring out the questions I wanted to answer I created graphs to provide me with my answers.

There is a trend between the alcohol content and the quality of the wine. There is also a trend between the volatile acidity and the quality of the wine.

With the observations provided average quality made up almost 75% of the observations. In order to run further analysis there could be double the observations, or a larger data set for individuals to answer. Maybe add age, country, or state to be collected and see if there is correlation to rankings.
